snippet.textDisplay:
I think this requires some thought and could depend on rules of the 2v2 and size of the court who would win. Also you have a true 2 and a true 5 in Kobe and Shaq vs. a 3 and a 4 in LBJ and AD. It’s not and equal match.

If it’s “make it take it” Shaq n Kobe all day. But if it’s change possession then Shaq compromises the team on D because LBJ and AD don’t have to go in the paint to score and I don’t think Kobe can shut them down for an entire game by himself. Now on a smaller court I think prime Shaq might be able to hang but not a NBA half court.

Then mentally, Shaq and Kobe would have the edge... two trash talking Alphas that are WANT to kill. LBJ CAN kill but he doesn’t always want to.

Big respect to all of them but I would love to hear this argument in the barbershop lol.

snippet.textDisplay: C'mon people please learn to give respect to the body of work of an all time great. In his prime Kobe Bryant ruled the NBA he was the most complete offensive and defensive player on the court. As great as Magic was and I do believe he is the second greatest Laker of all time, it was always a toss up between Larry Bird and Magic, and then Jordan just eclipsed the both of them. In his prime Kobe Bryant had no equal and nobody is even mentioning him as a scoring threat in the conversation. Tell it to the guys who had to put their entire teams in the peak of as talented and competitive West failing to stop Kobe when he got hot. Jerry West with due respect failed to topple the Celtics in his prime. The what ifs are great then what if Shaq didn't leave L.A for a larger paycheck, what if Kobe had the same health as LeBron and never got injured what if Lakers didn't lose the finals in '04 and '08 and made it to the finals in '11 (We'd had our Kobe vs LeBron). You know what that means it would've been no contest. And just comparing pound for pound, achievement for achievement Kobe Bryant is the greatest Laker ever, please respect that.
